	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0348">348<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0348.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Lahaie 26 Oct. 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Depuis quelque temps, &amp; plus les apparences de guerre se fortifient, plus je me trouve obsde, tant par des Americains que par
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0349">[349<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0349.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
des Hollandois, pour leur procurer des Lettres de mer Amricaines. Il mest ais de me dfaire de ces derniers, quoiquils reviennent toujours  la charge, en leur disant que cela nest pas en mon pouvoir, &amp; en leur promettant den crire  V. E. Mais il nen est pas demme des Amricains, qui se plaignent hautement de ne pas trouver ici le recours auquel ils ont droit de sattendre. Ils disent quils ne sauroient faire leurs affaires, sans tre assurs dtre aids sur le champ, lorsquelles viennent  lexiger; &amp; je conois quils ont raison. Entre autres il sest prsent un Mr. C. Dutilh March<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">d.</span> de Rotterdam, &amp; J<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">n.</span> Veder patron de Navire, accompagns de Mr. La Baussaie Ag<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t.</span> de France. Ils mont fait voir une Procure de Mr. Et. Dutilh, leur parent, Ng<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t.</span> tabli  Philadelphie, chargeant le dit Mr. C. Dutilh dacheter un Vaisseau pour compte de lui E. Dutilh, que le dit J<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">n.</span> Veder, qui ma produit son Acte de Bourgeois de Philadelphie, devoit comander &amp; conduire avec la cargaison quon y mettroit,  Philadelphie. Aprs avoir consult nos amis l-dessus, &amp; notament Mr. De Berenger, qui mon dit que je ferois mal de ne pas prendre sur moi daider ces gens, je leur promis de leur donner une Dclaration, qui pt servir de Lettre de mer, sils mexhiboient lActe lgal &amp; authentique de la Vente du Vaisseau, autrement nom ici transport, &amp; le Manifeste de sa Cargaison. Quelques jours aprs ils lont fait; &amp; en consquence je leur ai donn (NB. gratis, ce dont jai la dclaration signe du Capitaine) une Dclaration, dont voici copie, dans laquelle jai suivi le plus exactement possible le modele qui sen trouve dans le Trait de Comerce conclu ici par V. E. Jai seulement omis lapostrophe aux Empereurs, rois, &amp;c. qui et t absurde de ma part.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> Ce Vaisseau est dj en route pour Philadelphie.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Un autre Amricain, que jai promis daider sous les mmes conditions, &amp; qui peut revenir dun jour  lautre me somer de lui tenir parole, cest Mr. Wildick, Citoyen &amp; propritaire de terres en Pensylvanie, &amp; dun Vaisseau nouvellement bti  Philadelphie, dont il ma fait voir les Actes, lequel ma t recomand par le Col. Senf. Mr. Wildick ma observ, que si je ne voulois pas laider en cela, des Ngociants Anglois profiteroient des Marchs que lui ne pourroit conclure en ce cas.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Jai dj donn connoissance de lun &amp; lautre cas dans mes dernieres Lettres au Prsident du Congrs.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> En attendant, come cela ne laisse pas de minquiter, quoique jaie cru faire pour le mieux, je prie V. E. de vouloir bien mcrire le plutt possible votre sentiment l-dessus; &amp; sil y a de linconvnient  le faire  lavenir, de
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0350">[350<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0350.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
mautoriser  refuser la chose  dautres qui pourront se prsenter.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Quant aux Hollandois, lhonntet veut que je puisse aussi leur allguer les raisons au moins de mon impuissance  leur faire plaisir.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Par exemple, je ne sais que rpondre  Mess. W<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">m.</span> &amp; J<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">n.</span> Willink, qui me demandent par Lettre pressante du 12, si je pourrois leur procurer des papiers Amricains pour leur Vaisseaux, qui se trouvent actuellement dans differents ports, afin dobvier aux obstacles que les circonstances actuelles peuvent occasionner; me priant instament, si cela toit faisable, de les informer des particularits qui y sont attaches, pour ne jouer qu coup sr, &amp; pour prvenir toutes sortes dempechemens. Un autre Ngociant, Mr. Beud, connu de V. E. dit-il, est venu exprs de Rotterd, me consulter sur pareille affaire. Enfin Mr. Gallois, Courtier de Vaisseaux  Amst<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">m.</span>, mest venu parler aussi, &amp; puis ma envoy le Mmoire ci-joint, afin dy avoir une rponse, que je lui ai fait esprer de la part de Votre Excellence.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Dans ce moment je reois une Lettre de Mr. R. Wildick dAmst<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">m.</span>, qui allegue, quil nest pas juste de faire aux Amricain des difficults ici, quon ne leur fait point en Amriq<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span>, o il leur est permis de prendre pour Capitaines de leurs Vaisseaux des gens habiles de toute nation. Mr. Brush ma confirm cela. Il se plaint aussi des droits considrables quil faut payer en ce pays pour acheter lgalement un Vaisseau, &amp; voudroit les pargner. Je lui rponds sur cet Article, quil ne dpend pas de moi de dispenser les Amricains de ces droits du pays; mais que je ne saurois lui donner Dclaration quil demande, Sil ne me produit lActe de Vente pass lgalement devant le Magistrat, qui fasse voir que le Vaisseau est vraiment de proprit Americaine.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="translation">
        <h2>TRANSLATION</h2>
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 26 October 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">For some time, and all the more so as war becomes more likely, I have been importuned equally by Americans and Dutchmen to procure them American sea letters. It is easy for me to get rid of the latter, although they always try anew, by telling them that it is not in my power and promising them to write to your excellency about it. But it is not the same with the Americans, who complain loudly of not finding here the recourse that they have a right to expect. They say that they cannot conduct their business without being assured of receiving help immediately when they call for it, and I believe they are right. Among others who presented themselves were
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0351">[351<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0351.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
a Mr. Christian Dutilh, merchant of Rotterdam, and John Veder, owner of a ship, accompanied by Mr. La Baussaie, an agent from France. They showed me a power of attorney from Mr. tienne Dutilh, their parent, a merchant in business at Philadelphia, directing the said Mr. Christian Dutilh to purchase a vessel on the account of tienne Dutilh, which the said John Veder, who showed me his certificate of residency from Philadelphia, was to command and conduct, with a cargo that he was to put aboard, to Philadelphia. After consulting our friends on this matter, notably Mr. Brenger, who told me that it would be bad for me not to take it upon myself to help these people, I promised to give them a declaration, which could serve as a sea letter, if they would produce the vessels legal and authentic bill of sale, otherwise known here as the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">transport,</span> and the cargo manifest. Several days later they did so, and in consequence I gave to them (n.b. free of charge, for which I have a receipt signed by the captain) a declaration, a copy of which is enclosed, in which I followed as exactly as possible the model found in the treaty of commerce concluded by your excellency. I omitted only the apostrophe to emperors, kings, etc., which would have been absurd on my part.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> This vessel is already en route to Philadelphia.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Another American, whom I promised to help under the same conditions and who any day may call upon me to keep my word to him, is Mr. Wildick, citizen and owner of lands in Pennsylvania and owner of a vessel newly built at Philadelphia, for which he showed me the legal documents, and who was recommended to me by Col. Senf. Mr. Wildick observed to me that if I did not wish to help him in this matter, then English merchants would profit from the deals that he could not make.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I have already reported on both cases in my last letters to the president of Congress.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> While waiting, as this does not cease to worry me, even though I did what I thought was for the best, I beg your excellency to be so kind as to write to me as soon as possible your opinion on this matter and, if there is some disadvantage to doing it in the future, to authorize me to refuse the thing to others who might present themselves.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">As for the Dutch, honesty demands that I should at least give them the reasons for my inability to accommodate their wishes.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">For example, I do not know how to respond to Messrs. Wilhem and Jan Willink, who asked me in an urgent letter of the 12th if I could procure for them American papers for their vessels, which are now to be found in various ports, in order to obviate the obstacles that present circumstances could give rise to, earnestly entreating me, if it was possible, to inform them of the particulars involved so that they might act without risk and forestall all kinds of impediments. Another merchant, Mr. Beud, known to your excellency, so he says, came from Rotterdam expressly to consult me about a similar affair. Finally, Mr. Gallois, shipbroker at Amsterdam, also came to speak with me and then sent me the enclosed memorandum in order to obtain a response, as I led him to hope, from your excellency.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Just now I received a letter from Mr. R. Wildick of Amsterdam, which
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0352">[352<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0352.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
urges that it is not right to create difficulties for Americans here that they do not face at all in America, where they are permitted to take on as captains of their vessels able people of every nation. Mr. Brush confirmed this. He also complains of the considerable duties that one must pay in this country to legally purchase a vessel and would like to save them. To that point I respond that it does not rest with me to exempt Americans from the duties of this country, but I would not know how to give him the declaration that he asks for, unless he produces for me the bill of sale legally passed before the magistrate, which shows that the vessel is truly American property.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-sn">
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> and enclosures (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: Paris  S. E. M. Adams M. P. des E. U.; endorsed: M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Dumas. 13 Oct. / 1784. The endorsement refers to the date of the enclosures, for which see note 1.</p>

        </div>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0001">1</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The enclosures with this letter in the <span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span> are copies of the sea letter that Dumas issued for the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dispatch,</span> Capt. John Veder, on 13 Oct. and the receipt that Veder gave in return on the same day (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:521522, 528529). Dumas sea letter differed from the form appended to the 1782 Dutch-American Treaty of Amity and Commerce (vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0162-0011-0001#ADMS-06-13-02-pb-0378" class="pageNo">13:378379</a>) not only by omitting the ceremonial salutation but also by citing evidence of the nationality of the vessel beyond the simple oath of the captain, including the bill of sale and the certificate of cargo.</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0002">2</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Dumas explained how he came to issue a sea letter for the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dispatch</span> in a letter to the president of Congress that he wrote on the same day13 Oct. 1784and with which he enclosed another copy of Veders receipt (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early nineteenth century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e., the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 93, III, f. 55, 63; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:521522). He noted his promise of a sea letter to R. Wildick on the same proof of American citizenship and ownership in a 16 Oct. addendum to his 12 Oct. letter to Congress (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early nineteenth century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e., the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 93, III, f. 4647; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:522).</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0003">3</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> responded to Dumas plea for guidance regarding the issuance of sea letters in <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0238" class="document">his 3 Nov. reply</a>, below.</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0230-fn-0004">4</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This enclosure, not found, consisted of a series of questions asked by Amsterdam shipbroker Theodore Gallois regarding sea letters and other ships papers for American vessels. For a copy of the questions and <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s answers, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0237" class="document">his 3 Nov. letter to the president of Congress</a>, below. Gallois received a sea letter from Dumas for the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Porpoise,</span> Capt. Miles Casson, on 25 Nov., for which see <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0255" class="document">Dumas to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>, 1 Dec.</a>, and note 2, below, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from  1783, to  1789,&lt;/i&gt; [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, D.C., 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789,</span></span> 3:532534.</p>

        </div>

      </div>
